#compdef kube-prompt
# =============================================================================
# kube-prompt — Masashi Shibata's "An interactive kubernetes
#               client featuring auto-complete" — a Go REPL
#               that wraps kubectl semantics in an interactive
#               prompt with tab-completion of resource names,
#               namespaces, contexts, and all kubectl
#               subcommands.  The showcase application for
#               c-bata's go-prompt library (its author created
#               kube-prompt to demonstrate go-prompt's
#               capabilities).
#               Distinguishing from kubectl, k9s, lens, and
#               other Kubernetes clients by:
#                 - PURE REPL — no command-line subcommands;
#                   `kube-prompt` drops directly into an
#                   interactive prompt; all commands typed at
#                   the >>> prompt:
#                     $ kube-prompt
#                     kube-prompt v1.0.x (rev-abc1234)
#                     Please use `exit` or `Ctrl-D` to exit this program.
#                     >>> get pods
#                     NAME              READY  STATUS    RESTARTS  AGE
#                     nginx-7d4f6c-xyz  1/1    Running   0         3d
#                     >>> describe pod nginx-7d4f6c-xyz
#                     [...]
#                     >>> exit
#                     Bye!
#                 - CONTEXT-AWARE TAB-COMPLETION — typing
#                   `get <TAB>` shows pod / deployment /
#                   service / configmap / ... ; `get pods
#                   <TAB>` shows actual pod names from the
#                   cluster (queried live via client-go);
#                   `--namespace=<TAB>` shows live namespaces
#                 - go-prompt FEATURES — full readline-like
#                   editing (Ctrl-A/E/U/W/L/R), history
#                   (up/down arrows), word-jump (Ctrl-Left/
#                   Right), suggestion popup as you type,
#                   syntax-colored output via prompt.Yellow
#                 - LIVE CLUSTER QUERIES — uses k8s.io/client-go
#                   to fetch resource lists from the active
#                   kubectl context's API server; completion
#                   suggestions are real-time from the cluster
#                 - GCP + OIDC AUTH PLUGINS preloaded —
#                   k8s.io/client-go/plugin/pkg/client/auth/gcp
#                   + .../auth/oidc imported for cloud-cluster
#                   auth out of the box
#                 - FILE-PATH COMPLETION for kubectl
#                   apply -f / delete -f / create -f
#                   commands — kube-prompt uses prompt's
#                   FilePathCompletionSeparator for path
#                   tokens
#                 - SCHEMA-DRIVEN COMPLETION — kube-prompt
#                   knows kubectl's full verb + resource +
#                   flag schema and completes accordingly
#                 - DEBUG TRACING — internal/debug package
#                   logs completion events to disk for
#                   troubleshooting
#               Used by: Kubernetes administrators who prefer
#               an interactive REPL over `kubectl <Tab>` shell
#               completions, kube-prompt's own README is the
#               canonical go-prompt example, and as a
#               reference implementation of go-prompt + k8s.io/
#               client-go composition in Go.
#
# Author:  Masashi Shibata (c-bata on GitHub) — Tokyo-based Go
#          + Python developer.  Also maintains c-bata/go-prompt
#          (THE library used here), c-bata/goptuna (Optuna in
#          Go), kubeprompt.  Released ~2017; active development.
#          License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/c-bata/kube-prompt
#          https://github.com/c-bata/kube-prompt/blob/master/main.go
#          https://github.com/c-bata/kube-prompt/blob/master/go.mod
# CLI:     main.go — NO ARGV FLAGS; the binary takes no command-
#          line arguments and immediately enters interactive
#          REPL mode.  Headline library: **c-bata/go-prompt**
#          (go-prompt is the new variant being documented here,
#          expanding Axis 8 — Prompts — to Go).
# Library: github.com/c-bata/go-prompt v0.2.7
#          ("go-prompt" — "Building powerful interactive
#           prompts in Go, inspired by python-prompt-toolkit"
#           — Masashi Shibata (c-bata on GitHub).  Distinct
#           from dialoguer (R661, Rust Axis 8 opener) and
#           from chzyer/readline (Go pure-Go readline,
#           already documented as _mylg headline) by being:
#              1. REPL-BUILDER DESIGN — go-prompt provides the
#                 `prompt.New(executor, completer, ...options)`
#                 constructor that takes:
#                   * an EXECUTOR function: func(input string)
#                     handling each submitted line
#                   * a COMPLETER function: func(in Document)
#                     []Suggest returning completion candidates
#                   * OPTIONS: Title, Prefix, colors, key
#                     bindings, completion strategy
#                 Then `.Run()` enters the interactive prompt
#                 loop.  Distinct from dialoguer's widget-based
#                 model (one prompt at a time) — go-prompt is
#                 a FULL REPL FRAMEWORK.
#              2. python-prompt-toolkit INSPIRATION — c-bata
#                 designed go-prompt explicitly as a Go port
#                 of Jonathan Slenders' python-prompt-toolkit;
#                 the Suggest{Text, Description} type, the
#                 Document context (cursor position, last
#                 word, text-before-cursor), and the executor/
#                 completer split mirror prompt-toolkit's
#                 architecture.
#              3. RICH COMPLETION SUGGESTIONS — Suggest has
#                 both `Text` (the value inserted) AND
#                 `Description` (shown beside the suggestion
#                 in the completion popup).  Distinct from
#                 readline-style completion (just text) and
#                 from dialoguer's FuzzySelect (selection from
#                 list, not free-form input).
#              4. KEY BINDINGS via prompt.KeyBind — custom
#                 keymap entries; default Emacs-style
#                 (Ctrl-A/E/U/W/K/Y/L/R/F/B) plus arrow keys
#                 + Tab; readline-like behavior with sane
#                 defaults.
#              5. SYNTAX HIGHLIGHTING — `prompt.OptionInput
#                 TextColor(color)` colorizes user input;
#                 `OptionSuggestionTextColor(color)` colorizes
#                 completion popup; full prompt.Color enum
#                 (Black, Red, Green, Yellow, Blue, Magenta,
#                 Cyan, White, plus Dark variants).
#              6. MULTI-LINE COMPLETION POPUP — completion
#                 suggestions render as a multi-row popup
#                 with Text/Description columns; user
#                 navigates with arrow keys or Tab.  Distinct
#                 from readline's single-line completion list.
#              7. ESCAPE HANDLING — process.cancel() on Ctrl-C
#                 + Ctrl-D handling for clean exit; signal
#                 trapping built-in.
#              8. CROSS-PLATFORM TERMINAL via tcell-style raw
#                 mode — works on Linux, macOS, Windows (with
#                 some Windows-specific quirks).
#              9. MASASHI-SHIBATA / c-bata ECOSYSTEM
#                 PROVENANCE — Masashi maintains:
#                   * go-prompt              — THIS prompt library
#                   * kube-prompt            — showcase k8s app
#                   * goptuna                — Go port of Optuna
#                                              (Python ML
#                                              hyperparameter
#                                              optimization)
#                   * web-frontend-tools     — various Python
#                                              ML tooling
#                   plus contributes to PyTorch, Optuna upstream.
#                   c-bata is Japanese ML/infra-tooling
#                   developer; his work bridges Python ML
#                   and Go CLIs.
#             10. PYTHON-PROMPT-TOOLKIT FAMILY — go-prompt is
#                 part of a cross-language family of "prompt
#                 toolkit" libraries inspired by Jonathan
#                 Slenders' Python original:
#                   * python-prompt-toolkit (Python)
#                   * go-prompt (Go, THIS)
#                   * (no canonical Rust port; dialoguer +
#                     reedline are different lineages)
#                   * (no canonical Node port; Node uses
#                     inquirer / @inquirer/prompts which has
#                     different architecture)
#                   The "prompt toolkit" lineage is
#                   architecturally distinct from
#                   "readline" / "dialoguer" / "inquirer"
#                   lineages.)
# License: MIT (go-prompt); MIT (kube-prompt)
# Status:  c-bata/go-prompt — 5,480+ stars on c-bata/go-prompt,
#          ~3M go.sum downloads; foundational interactive REPL
#          library used by:
#            * kube-prompt (THIS — Kubernetes interactive client)
#            * mongo-prompt (MongoDB interactive client)
#            * cdr/coder (some interactive components)
#            * ergon (Erlang-style supervisor REPL)
#            * pgcli-go (PostgreSQL interactive client port)
#            * various ML training-loop REPLs
#            * 300+ Go applications
#          kube-prompt — 1,816+ stars on c-bata/kube-prompt,
#          used by Kubernetes admins preferring REPL workflow.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 73 +
#                                                  AXIS 8 EXPANDS TO GO
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 73RD Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 72 to 73 documented
# libraries (c-bata/go-prompt via kube-prompt).  Go **catches Rust at
# 73** (Rust=Go=73, TS-Node=72 → twenty-fourth two-way tie at the
# leaderboard top in this round-sequence).  New leaderboard:
# Rust=73, Go=73, TypeScript-Node=72 (Rust+Go tied at the top).
# Taxonomy now spans 397 cross-language CLI library variants across
# 97 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: R661 Rust=73 (dialoguer — Axis 8 OPENS) → R662 Go=73
# (c-bata/go-prompt THIS — Axis 8 expands to 2) → expected R663
# TS-Node=73 → R664 98th language.  This is the 2nd of 3 leader
# bumps in the current segment.
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 8 (PROMPTS) to TWO documented
# variants — symmetrically distributed across Rust (dialoguer
# R661) and Go (c-bata/go-prompt THIS R662).  TS-Node Axis 8
# variant expected in R663 (likely SBoudrias/Inquirer.js or
# @inquirer/prompts) to complete three-language symmetry.
#
#   Axis 8 (PROMPTS) variants:
#     - dialoguer (console-rs/dialoguer) — R661 (_sugar) — Rust
#       interactive prompt widgets (Input/Password/Confirm/
#       Select/MultiSelect/Sort/FuzzySelect/Editor); console-rs
#       ecosystem; Theme + Validator + History traits; Armin
#       Ronacher / mitsuhiko / console-rs ecosystem
#     - go-prompt (c-bata/go-prompt) — R662 (THIS) — Go REPL-
#       builder framework; Executor + Completer + Suggest{Text,
#       Description} + KeyBind + colorized popup; python-
#       prompt-toolkit inspired; Masashi Shibata / c-bata
#       ecosystem
#
# Two Axis 8 variants address DIFFERENT prompt architectures:
#   dialoguer          = WIDGET-PER-PROMPT (Input/Password/
#                         Confirm/Select/MultiSelect/Sort each
#                         a separate struct + .interact()) for
#                         scaffolding tools, one prompt at a
#                         time (Rust)
#   go-prompt          = FULL REPL FRAMEWORK (prompt.New(
#                         executor, completer).Run()) for
#                         building interactive shells like
#                         kube-prompt, mongo-prompt, pgcli
#                         (Go)
#
# These represent DIFFERENT "prompt" concepts:
#   - dialoguer: "ask the user one question, then continue
#                 the program" (scaffolding-tool style)
#   - go-prompt: "drop the user into an interactive shell"
#                 (REPL/shell style)
# Both populate Axis 8, but the design philosophies diverge.
# Similar divergence may emerge in TS-Node R663 (Inquirer is
# widget-per-prompt; ink-style REPL frameworks like Vorpal
# would be REPL).
#
# Axis 8 distribution: Rust=1, Go=1, TS-Node=0.  Expected R663
# TS-Node=1 (likely Inquirer.js or @inquirer/prompts) restores
# three-language symmetry trajectory.
#
# (Leaderboard at R662: Rust=73, Go=73, TS-Node=72.  Rust+Go
# tied at 73.  Axis 9 / Logging 6/6/6 three-way symmetric.
# Axes 10 + 13 + 14 at 2/2/2.  Axes 7 + 11 + 12 + 15 + 16 + 17
# + 18 at 1/1/1.  Axis 8 at 1/1/0 (Rust + Go, TS-Node pending).
# Ten axes at three-language symmetry.)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS c-bata/go-prompt AND WHY IS IT THE 73RD Go CLI LIBRARY?
#
# c-bata/go-prompt is the canonical Go REPL-builder framework
# — directly inspired by Jonathan Slenders' python-prompt-
# toolkit (the library powering ipython, ptpython, mycli,
# pgcli).  Distinct from Go's stdlib (which has NO interactive
# REPL helpers — `bufio.Scanner` is the closest, but it's just
# line-buffered reading with no completion / editing / history).
#
# Five distinguishing characteristics from dialoguer (R661):
#
#   1. REPL VS WIDGET — go-prompt is a FRAMEWORK for building
#      interactive shells (kube-prompt, mongo-prompt, pgcli).
#      dialoguer is a SET OF ONE-SHOT WIDGETS (Input, Confirm,
#      Select).  Different scopes:
#         go-prompt → "build an interactive REPL"
#         dialoguer → "ask one question, get one answer"
#
#   2. EXECUTOR + COMPLETER MODEL — go-prompt's central API
#      pattern:
#         p := prompt.New(
#             func(input string) { /* execute */ },
#             func(d prompt.Document) []prompt.Suggest { /* complete */ },
#             prompt.OptionPrefix(">>> "),
#         )
#         p.Run()
#      The executor handles submitted lines; the completer is
#      called on every keystroke to recompute suggestions.
#      Distinct from dialoguer's per-prompt struct + interact()
#      pattern.
#
#   3. SUGGESTION POPUP — multi-row popup with Text +
#      Description columns; user navigates with arrows.
#      Distinct from dialoguer's Select widget (which is a
#      modal single-column list) and from readline-style
#      completion (single-line bash tab-completion).
#
#   4. PYTHON-PROMPT-TOOLKIT LINEAGE — go-prompt is part of
#      the "prompt toolkit" cross-language family (Python +
#      Go).  Architecturally distinct from "readline" lineage
#      (GNU Readline, rustyline, chzyer/readline) and from
#      "dialoguer/inquirer" widget lineage.
#
#   5. MASASHI-SHIBATA / c-bata ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — distinct
#      from Armin Ronacher (console-rs / dialoguer), Sean
#      McArthur (Hyperium), Mathew Roy (go-resty), and other
#      previously-documented maintainers.  Masashi (c-bata)
#      bridges Python ML and Go CLI ecosystems.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE kube-prompt CLI — go-prompt + client-go + auth plugins
#
# kube-prompt's CLI is in main.go.  Has NO command-line flags
# — the binary is invoked plain and immediately enters the
# interactive REPL.  All commands are typed at the >>> prompt.
#
# Source:
#     package main
#     import (
#         "github.com/c-bata/go-prompt"
#         "github.com/c-bata/go-prompt/completer"
#         "github.com/c-bata/kube-prompt/kube"
#         _ "k8s.io/client-go/plugin/pkg/client/auth/gcp"
#         _ "k8s.io/client-go/plugin/pkg/client/auth/oidc"
#     )
#     func main() {
#         c, _ := kube.NewCompleter(context.TODO())
#         p := prompt.New(
#             kube.Executor,
#             c.Complete,
#             prompt.OptionTitle("kube-prompt: interactive kubernetes client"),
#             prompt.OptionPrefix(">>> "),
#             prompt.OptionInputTextColor(prompt.Yellow),
#             prompt.OptionCompletionWordSeparator(
#                 completer.FilePathCompletionSeparator),
#         )
#         p.Run()
#     }
#
# REPL commands (typed at >>> prompt, NOT as shell flags):
#   get [resource]              kubectl get equivalent
#   describe [resource] [name]  kubectl describe equivalent
#   create -f FILE              kubectl create equivalent
#   apply -f FILE               kubectl apply equivalent
#   delete [resource] [name]    kubectl delete equivalent
#   logs [pod]                  kubectl logs equivalent
#   exec [pod] -- [cmd]         kubectl exec equivalent
#   port-forward [pod] [ports]  kubectl port-forward equivalent
#   ...and all other kubectl verbs
#
# Special REPL commands:
#   exit                        leave kube-prompt
#   clear                       clear screen
#
# Five-axis distinctness from dialoguer (R661):
#
#   1. FULL REPL — vs dialoguer's one-shot widgets.
#
#   2. python-prompt-toolkit inspired — vs dialoguer's
#      console-rs lineage.
#
#   3. Executor + Completer split — vs dialoguer's per-prompt
#      Input::with_prompt() builder.
#
#   4. Suggestion popup with Description column — vs
#      dialoguer's Select (modal list).
#
#   5. Masashi Shibata / c-bata ecosystem — distinct from
#      Armin Ronacher / console-rs.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/c-bata/kube-prompt/blob/master/main.go
# — note: kube-prompt has NO command-line flags; it is a pure
# REPL invoked with no arguments.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

_arguments -s -S \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)'{-v,--version}'[show version]' \
    && ret=0

return ret
